Hey, here’s my use case: I have a component/directive which have a Boolean input property. I often use Angular/cdk in my projects because it offers useful features we don’t need to rewrite. One of it is the coercion of properties and more precisely the coerceBooleanProperty() method. You know there are many way to bind boolean attributes on DOM element.
<button disabled=“true”>Click</button>

<button [disabled]=“true”>Click</button>

<button disabled>Click</button>

In Typescript files this will be converted in a boolean or a string and it had a difficulty to handle it.
A first approach, is to use getter/setter and to call the cdk method to always have a boolean value.
@Input()
set disabled(disabled) {
  this._disabled = cerceBooleanProperty(disabled);
}

get disabled(): boolean {
  return this._disabled;
}

private _disabled: boolean;

But I find that a lot of code to repeat each time.
@Input()
@CoerceBoolean()
public disabled: boolean;

Here’s the code of the decorator which allows to do it:
import { coerceBooleanProperty } from '@angular/cdk/coercion';

export function CoerceBoolean() {
    return function (target: any, key: string): void {
        const getter = function () {
            // using Typescript reflection
            return this['__' + key];
        };

        const setter = function (next: any) {
            // using Typescript reflection
            this['__' + key] = coerceBooleanProperty(next);
        };

        Object.defineProperty(target, key, {
            get: getter,
            set: setter,
            enumerable: true,
            configurable: true,
        });
    };
}

Thanks for reading. Feel free to let me know your questions or how you handle it in your projects.

Hey here is my use case: I have a component/directive which required inputs.
@Directive()
export class MyDirective {
  @Input()
  public requiredInput!: unknown;

  @Input()
  public optionalInput?: unknown;
}

I use the ‘!’ operator to mark requiredInput as mandatory initialized.
To improve this I can add a check in OnInit hook.
@Directive()
export class MyDirective implements OnInit {
  @Input()
  public requiredInput!: unknown;

  @Input()
  public optionalInput?: unknown;

  public ngOnInit(): void {
    if(!this.requiredInput) {
      throw new Error(‘…’);
    }
  }
}

But I have to admit that I’m a bit lazy and I don’t want to do that each time I need to check my input(s).
@Directive()
@RequiredInputs([‘requiredInput’])
export class MyDirective {
  @Input()
  public requiredInput!: unknown;

  @Input()
  public optionalInput?: unknown;
}

Do you know the Typescript decorator? If you don’t here’s the official doc
Now let me present you the decorator code which allow to write the code above:

export function RequiredInputs(inputs: string[]) {
    return function (constructor: any) {
        const original = constructor.prototype.ngOnInit;

        constructor.prototype.ngOnInit = function () {
            inputs.forEach((input: string) => {
                if (this[input] === undefined) {
                    throw new Error(`property ${input} is mandatory ${constructor.prototype.name}`);
                }
            });

            if (original && typeof original === 'function') {
                original.apply(this, arguments);
            }
        };
    };
}

That’s all. Feel free to comment and tell me how tou handle this use case.
Thanks for reading.

